<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Hesperocyparis pigmaea </i>trees grow to 2 m in height on sterile soils and to 50 m in height on more fertile soils. Cone production is abundant on dwarfed, mature trees. The closed cones persist on the tree until opened by heat, desiccation, or age. Seeds fall gradually over several months after cones open. Seed germination and seedling establishment are best on bare mineral soil. Seedling mortality is high with shade and litter because of damping-off fungi (Barbour 2007, Vogl et al. 1977). Botanists have considered <i>H. pigmaea </i>a subspecies <i>H. goveniana </i>(Hickman 1993), but recent genetic study (Bartel et al. 2003) showed <i>H. pigmaea </i>to be closer to <i>H. sargentii </i>than to <i>H. goveniana.</i> Both <i>H. pigmaea</i> and <i>H. goveniana</i> are rare and appear as CNPS list 1B.2 plants. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Hesperocyparis abramsiana </i>is a fast-growing evergreen tree to 15 m in height that lives to 200 years. Trees begin bearing cones in the first decade of age. The serotinous cones usually remain closed on the plants after maturity. Seed dispersal can occur without fire, but many open and disperse seeds when heated by fire. Seedling establishment is best on bare soil. Seedling mortality is high on shaded sites with abundant litter because of damping-off fungi. Developing plants create dense thickets or individual plants with other tree and shrub species. Plants are intolerant of shade, and groves tend to be single aged. On extreme sites, scattered plants are highly stunted (USFWS 1987).  <i>H. abramsiana </i>is a CNPS list 1B.2 plant that is also state and federally listed as endangered, and two subspecies have been recognized: var. <i> abramsiana</i> and var. <i>butanoensis</i> (Adams and Bartel 2009).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Hesperocyparis macrocarpa </i>is a coastal conifer that attains a height of 25 m. Only two native groves exist on the Monterey Peninsula. It is shaped or distorted by salt and wind blasting directly along the coastline, but a short distance inland, it is erect. Estimates of maximum plant age are 200-300 years (Esser 1994f). Descriptions (Barbour 2007, Vogl et al. 1977) suggest that <i>H. macrocarpa </i>associates with other alliances rather than forming its own. <i>H. macrocarpa </i>is a rare, CNPS list 1B.2 plant.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Hesperocyparis goveniana </i>is an endemic cypress on the Monterey Peninsula, which is dwarfed by acidic, shallow terrace soils that flood in the winter and desiccate in the summer. Trees grow to 5 m in height on sterile soils and to 50 m in height on fertile ones. Cone production is abundant on dwarfed and mature trees, but it is rare or absent on young vigorous trees. Cones are closed; they persist on the tree until opened by the heat of a fire or from desiccation due to age (Esser 1994d). <br/>
<br/>
The genus <i>Cupressus </i>is now restricted to the Old World; cypresses in California belong to the genus <i>Hesperocyparis </i>(Bartel et al. 2003, Little 2006, Adams et al. 2009, Terry et al. 2012).<br/>
<br/>
The four rare species <i>Hesperocyparis</i> included in this alliance are restricted to coastal habitats.  Due to their similarity of habitat and associates, they are combined here in a single alliance.  Because of the rarity of the trees, stands of three of the species were treated as Special Stands rather than Alliances in the 2009 publication of <i>The Manual of California Vegetation, second edition</i>, under the genus <i>Callitropsis.</i>  Only stands of <i>Hesperocyparis pigmaea</i> were previously described at the alliance level, and VegCAMP (2019) has since evaluated and redefined the associations characterized by this taxon.  <br/>
<br/>
The plant/soil relations are striking on the marine terraces in Mendocino Co. (Jenny et al. 1969) where belts of tall forests containing <i>Picea sitchensis, Pinus muricata, Pseudotsuga menziesii, </i>and <i>Sequoia sempervirens </i>surround some 20 irregular patches of stunted, cane-like <i>Hesperocyparis pigmaea </i>on the older terraces. These patches of pygmy-sized trees occur in areas of soils with cemented hardpans that are extremely acidic and nutrient deficient. Stands of tall forest trees occur less frequently on these terraces and are restricted to less acidic, more nutrient-rich areas lacking hardpans. Water accumulates above the hardpans throughout the rainy season and floods the entire soil surface, creating anoxic conditions. Soils, however, remain wet during the dry season in the rooting zone, not desiccated above the hardpan as long thought (Sholars 1984). Stands of <i>H. goveniana </i>in Monterey Co. occur in similar site conditions, though even more localized, with both pygmy-sized trees and taller stature trees.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Hesperocyparis abramsiana </i>grows in San Mateo and Santa Cruz Cos. mostly on well-drained ridgelines above the <i>Sequoia sempervirens </i>forests on the slopes, canyons, and basins below. Individual trees and groves, both pure and with mixed composition, form a fine vegetation mosaic with other forest and chaparral types, variously described as coastal closed-pine forest, maritime Coast Range ponderosa pine forest, maritime chaparral, mixed chaparral, and mixed evergreen forest. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
