<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Hesperocyparis pigmaea </i>is fire adapted with serotinous cones; successful seeding establishment is generally restricted to recently burned sites. Its low-branching habit makes it susceptible to crown fires. Fires kill most or all low-stature trees; large trees may survive. Cones persist on the branches and open when exposed to heat, releasing large quantities of seeds (Stuart and Stephens 2006, Vogl et al. 1977). Most seed falls in the first few months following a fire (Zedler 1986). 

<i>H. abramsiana <i>responds similarly to fire in that mature trees are killed by fire, and seeds require light and bare mineral soil to germinate. Post-fire recruitment can be vigorous, and self-thinning can occur over time. Lacking fire, trees will senesce (USFWS 2013). While little information on fire return intervals exists for the alliance, stands may have a historic fire cycle of 35-100 years that is similar to maritime chaparral types (Van Dyke et al. 2001). <i>H. abramsiana <i> has experienced recent fire due to a recent 2008 Martin Road fire that covered half of the Bonny Doon population (USFWS 2013), and due to the 2020 CZU complex fire that spread across the populations, where long-term monitoring will be necessary to determine stand regeneration.

<i>H. macrocarpa</i> is easily killed by fire, and it typically regenerates from seed in serotinous cones as do other California cypresses. <i>H. macrocarpa</i> is capable of seedling establishment with or without crown fire because cones can open on warm days and shed seed without the aid of fire. However, fire provides optimum site conditions for regeneration. Large trees may survive surface fire; however, cypress thickets are conducive to crown fires, and most trees are killed (Esser 1994f). Although no information is available on fire return intervals, the current intervals may be too long to perpetuate existing stands.

<i>H. goveniana </i>is also a fire-adapted, fire-dependent species. Seeds banked in the abundant cones persistent on the branches will open when heated. Most seed falls in the first few months following fire. Trees make thickets with low branches that are conducive to crown fires, which usually kill almost all trees in the stand (Barbour 2007, Vogl et al. 1977).</div>
