    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>Scattered stands throughout the Central and Northern California Coast.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Af, Ah, Aj). Stands of <i>H. abramsiana </i>var. <i>butanoensis </i>occur only in San Mateo Co. on Butano Ridge with maritime chaparral endemic shrubs (e.g., <i>Arctostaphylos andersonii </i>and <i>A. crustacea</i>; Sikes et al. 2021).  Stands of <i>H. abramsiana </i>var. <i>abramsiana </i>occur in four locations in Santa Cruz Co. with <i>A. silvicola </i>and </i>A. sensitiva</i>. 

<i>H. goveniana </i> has two or three occurrences in Monterey Co., often called the Huckleberry Hill and Gibson Creek stands. It also occurs as scattered trees on shallow, poorly drained soils surrounded by <i>Pinus radiata </i>stands on deeper soils (Holland 1986). Associated shrubs include <i>A. hookeri, A. tomentosa, Ceanothus thyrsiflorus, </i>among others. Two native stands of <i>H. macrocarpa </i>occur along the Monterey Peninsula either as a sculpted woodland or with a grassy understory.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ag-i). Stands with <i>Hesperocyparis pigmaea</i> and <i>Pinus contorta</i> ssp. <i>bolanderi</i> occur between Pudding Creek and the Navarro River primarily in Mendocino Co. and scattered in northern Sonoma Co. Associated shrubs include <i>Arctostaphylos columbiana, A. nummularia, Rhododendron </i> spp., <i>Vaccinium ovatum</i>, among others. Other stands lacking the cypress south of the Navarro River are placed in the <i>Pinus muricata</i> alliance. Stands of <i>H. pigmaea</i> may include other rare plants including <i>Arctostaphylos nummularia</i> ssp. <i>mendocinoensis, Carex californica, Juncus supiniformis, Lilium maritimum, </i>and <i>Rhynchospora alba (VegCAMP 2019).</i></li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Residential development threatens the cypresses, especially for the <i>H. pigmaea </i>stands. Two associations including this species have been ranked as S1, <i>Hesperocyparis pigmaea - Pinus contorta</i> ssp. <i>bolanderi / Rhododendron columbianum</i> and <i>Hesperocyparis pigmaea - Pinus muricata / Arctostaphylos nummularia</i> Associations. Lichens, especially <i>Cladina portentosa </i>ssp. <i>pacifica, </i>create cryptogamic crusts in older stands, which are easily destroyed by foot traffic, fire, and air pollution. Ditches change the local hydrology, and leach lines from homes add nutrients. Both these changes, over time, impact the species composition and compromise community integrity. To maintain a stand, the fire return intervals should be long enough to allow a cone crop to develop, but short enough to maintain a viable seed bank in the trees (Sugihara et al. 2006). In this case, it would be better to consider ways to maintain the maximum number of mature stands as a preservation strategy for this species and the alliance.

Similarly for <i>H. abramsiana </i>, habitat loss through agriculture conversion, residential development, alteration of the natural fire frequency, and vandalism threaten the species. Also, genetic introgression from <i>Hesperocyparis macrocarpa </i>is of concern (Van Dyke et al. 2001).  High-level threat is due in part to lower levels of regeneration because of altered fire regimes, combined with lack of management that encourages recruitment (USFWS 2013). Other threats include reproductive isolation, climate change and invasive species (USFWS 2013).  The <i>Hesperocyparis abramsiana / Arctostaphylos </i>spp.<i> - Adenostoma fasciculatum</i> has been ranked as S1.

The <i>Hesperocyparis macrocarpa</i> Association has been ranked as S1, as has the <i>Hesperocyparis goveniana</i> Association. Suburban expansion has historically encroached upon the Cypress Point stand of <i>H. macrocarpa </i>in Pebble Beach. The other and largest native stand of <i>H. macrocarpa </i>at Point Lobos has an understory dominated by invasives, in which most of its understory is composed of the shade-tolerant, invasive grass <i>Ehrharta erecta.</i> Planted and naturalized stands of this species are common along the California coast, but are treated under a separate <i>Hesperocyparis macrocarpa - Pinus radiata</i> Semi-Natural Alliance. </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
